text: i believe if martin luther king jr was alive today he’d be so saddened by the incredible anger and abuse going on in the world today. we are not separate, and when we don’t speak up for those who are marginalized and suffering, it’s because we’ve forgotten that we share more things in common than we remember. we need to protect our most vulnerable and act with compassion. i truly believe mlk would speak out against donald trump’s wall, the imprisoning of immigrants, the pitting of poor white people against people of color, the degradation of women and lgbtq, the tearing apart of the epa, the defunding of the arts, the lack of morals and ethics and extreme lack of empathy. flint still doesn’t have water. our prisons are still disproportionately full of people of color serving lengthy sentences for non violent drug offenses. schools are falling apart. black people are having the police called on them for selling water, sitting in starbucks, barbecuing in the park, using their college library, etc. we all learn about the beautiful and unifying speeches given from the heart of mlk let’s today and everyday live these words. #love #mlk #familiesbelongtogether #metoo #blacklivesmatter #kneelwithkaepernick #schoolsnotprisons #healthcareforall #protectourwater #stopfracking #saveourplanet #lgbtqrightsarehumanrights #onelove

text:
»etiquetar es lo opuesto a entender«
-
para los que vieron #sense8 esa no será una frase que pase inadvertida, y me viene bien para hablar de algo que me ha estado molestando mucho los últimos dos días.
-
cuando increpan a los personajes de lito y capheus simultáneamente aparecen también los personajes protagónicos, y hablan del hecho de ser etiquetados.
-
hoy los venezolanos estamos compartiendo la etiqueta de asesinos; pagamos todos justos por pecadores; así dice el dicho ¿no?
-
lo cierto es que condeno cualquier acto violento no solo contra las mujeres sino también contra cada ser humano y viviente de la tierra. nada nos da derecho de tomar decisión sobre la vida de otro.
-
pero, ¿acaso no es este un hecho común en nuestros países? el feminicidio en latinoamérica alcanza números alarmantes, nuestra cultura machista asesina y reduce a las mujeres a diario; entonces, ¿qué hace distinto este hecho?
-
que un migrante venezolano, en un país que no es el de su origen cometió un terrible acto, mató a su novia a puñaladas y por eso ahora en medio de ésta gran diáspora es momento de decir que todos los venezolanos migrantes son asesinos, y por si no fuera suficiente también los que compartimos nacionalidad con ellos.
-
me parece absurdo, el hecho no es atacar a quienes compartimos nacionalidad, porqué mejor no nos vamos a la raíz de asunto, la violencia y el asesinato, sin que importe si es nativo de china o del congo, de ecuador o venezuela.
-
etiquetar, segmentar y de paso juzgar a todos por uno es absurdo, y lo es más cuando la atención debería ir al acto en sí sin importar quién o de dónde viene la persona que lo cometió.
-
responder el odio con odio no es la forma ni la respuesta, de esa manera seguirá pasando y el bucle se repetirá hasta que comprendamos que el crimen no viene incluido en nuestro fenotipo o condición geográfica.
-
veámonos sin fronteras, así de verdad iría mejor.
-
los quiero mucho 💛 más amor por favor.
-
-
#bitácorasdelermitaño #ermitañoescribe #ecuador #venezuela #feminicidio #niunamas #metoo #stop #sense8

text:
one component of raising awareness is ensuring people recognize the signs of domestic violence. everyone needs to know what it is and how to spot it happening in their lives or in the lives of their friends.

domestic violence can happen to anyone. it happens to all races, ages, sexual orientation, religion or gender. is domestic violence something that only happens between married couples? no. while domestic violence does apply to married couples, it can also occur between people who are living together or who are dating.

please read and share to help yourselves and other recognise the signs and how to deal with a domestic abuse situation safely.
.
.
.
.
.

domestic violence can happen to anyone. it happens to all races, ages, sexual orientation, religion or gender. is domestic violence something that only happens between married couples? no. while domestic violence does apply to married couples, it can also occur between people who are living together or who are dating.

please read and share to help yourselves and other recognise the signs and how to deal with a domestic abuse situation safely.
.

.
.
.

text:
from the @nytgender “most of us know names like rosa parks and fannie lou hamer — but there are dozens of other women who are less known but equally critical to the civil rights movement. ⠀
…⠀
…⠀
women like gloria richardson, who famously waved away the bayonet of a national guardsman during a protest in cambridge in 1963; dorothy height, the president of the national council of negro women, who would often be cropped out of pictures of organization presidents; ella baker, a field secretary and branch director of the naacp; and dorothy cotton, who taught students how to peacefully protest even as people taunted them, pushed them and threatened their lives.”⠀
…⠀
…⠀
these are women who risked everything including their safety to advance their cause - and yet we barely know them. when i saw gloria steinem’s play, #alife, i learned that black women inspired and also taught gloria everything she knows about activism, yet they were also cut from interviews while the media focused on gloria, the white, beautiful woman. it was eye-opening and extraordinarily sad to see great people marginalized. ⠀
…⠀
…⠀
“on this #mlkday, we’re remembering the unsung women who steered the movement” - ny times.⠀
.⠀
.⠀
.⠀

.

.
consistency is key! it’s been over a year since i was consistent with my running but like i said, i’ll get it back. and in 8 months will be crossing that ironman number 3 finish line!
.

"i have a dream that's similar to dr. king's
let freedom ring in the streets
i have a dream that there was nothin' left to protest
because all of god's people would treat each other equal
i have a dream that our blood-stained blocks with young men shot are now clean
no more shoulders cried on with mother's tears
i have a dream that the #metoo movement was not needed
and all of our women like queens they were treated
i have a dream that our soldiers came home and the war stopped
prison wasn't for profit, treating bodies like stocks
i have a dream
that from dawn until dusk
that we all know your love
till we turn into dust
oh god, i have a dream."
[song - "i have a dream" by derek minor]

i sit here on this martin luther king jr day resting in my comfortable suburban home in front of a roaring fire as i look outside at the snowfall in my front yard and  i am still trying to process what we just did.  3 years ago i joined brickxbrick, an art performance piece where we use our bodies to build human walls against rape culture and violence using trump’s disgusting words against women.  to decide to stand in the face of uncertainty at a national march, using your body as a billboard is terrifying to say the least.  you are completely exposed and vulnerable.  every single fear that you’ve ever had sits right there. with you, by you, and in front of your face. 
i look at this picture us in front of trump tower that made the washington post and now reuter’s- a global publication.  and i smile, but it still hasn’t soaked in.  last week i saw my image on shonda rhime’s time up video, and 2 years previous, it was the new york post and cnn online.  i can’t help but to be elated that these images will go down in herstory, but what does it all mean, and what do i do with it.

if you look at the diversity of faces in these pictures, you can see the diversity and complexity of issues with this movement.  it’s not just one thing, and it never will be.  women’s issues are complicated and have always been. and we deserve so much than we are getting and this is us demanding rights for ourselves.  i completely ignored the infighting, because that is just a distraction.  we have/had real work to do.  and no matter who’s at the top,  or what color hats we wore, or what the temperature was, i was not going to be stopped.  why? because there is work to do. “we show up.” period.  end of sentence. #cantstopwontstop #metoo #timesup #blacklivesmatter #blackgirlsrock #womenswave2019 #brickxbrick #risd #risd1877 #bebo #clamjam #sankofa

text:
•day 15•⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
30 days of s3x positive affirmations.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
🌟i am gentle with my healing🌟⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣take your time. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
listen to your body. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
follow your intuition. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
rest.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
do relaxing things.⁣⁣
⁣
receive. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
don’t overcommit. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
put yourself first.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
and, remember you are worthy and beautiful exactly the way you are.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
these are the things which have helped me on my own journey of healing s3xual trauma. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
although diving into tantra and practicing the jade egg have been a big part of my healing - it wouldn’t mean much without the things on this list. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i’ve been there: i’ve overcommitted, i’ve ignored my intuition and put other’s first. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
i’ve been hard on myself and not listened to my body. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
and honestly, it was all a guise. a way of bypassing what i really felt. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
but, trying to force myself out of these ways did not work either. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
and, so i took small, gentle steps. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i eased the pressure. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i nurtured myself and became more aware of my emotions. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i listened to my intuition. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i rested.⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i put myself first. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
slowly slowly i became more embodied and i was able to begin to let go of my hurt and shame. ⁣⁣⁣ ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣
there is still some hurt, there are still some barriers and sometimes there’s shame. i’m ok with that ☺️ ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
however, where i once felt numb i feel vibrant and alive. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
where i once felt scared to open to love i now love. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
i feel rich and juicy. and, mmmm i yearn for nothing more than to just keep opening and opening. ⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
be gentle with yourself peeps.
❤️⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣you’ve got this. ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
sweet dreams⁣⁣, and much love⁣⁣, ⁣⁣⁣
naia

text:
we marched to protest the deportation of refugees and undocumented people. for low-income immigrant families choosing between food stamps and a green card. for the disability community experiencing cuts to healthcare. for sex workers facing sesta/fosta. for families separated by the muslim ban, by child separation, by prison and border walls. for survivors saying #metoo. for black and brown people resisting police violence. for trans people facing erasure. for the land rights of indigenous people. and for so, so many more. we marched for all of us.

#womensmarch #womensmarch2019 #womenswave #riseup #intersectionalfeminism #whywemarch #thisiswhatdemocracylookslike #resist

text:
i had a dream. 
even before i knew  exactly what it was much less how to execute it. i look back now and think others may have thought i knew what i meant when i said  i wanted to help others feel like this! 🌟
but i had no clue there was already a plan in place and others were already doing it . 
i wanted to share this spark and power of feeling alive again! 💥
y’all this feeing needed to be shouted from the roof tops!!! it was too amazing to keep to myself. 
i had been depressed for so long and i fought back kicking, screaming and crying my way out of it with something simple as a workout and not just any workout one that touched my heart and seeped into  every part of my life. 
back then my workout was a hour long and i got up early and did it before my 40 hour a week job.  man looking back i had drive ! 
i had drive because my why was huge! 
my why was being  sick and tired of being stuck!  even my soul was tired . (do you know that feeling) ? 
it was something that was simple really . 
follow the calendar do the workout for that day.  that’s it. 
then i started taking pride in how my body was feeling so i started watching the food i was taking in plus girlfriend here needed some extra for those hours of sweat. 🌱
you see i didn’t know what i was doing i was just grasping for whatever was making me feel better. 
next i found this community of freaking amazing people that had the same experience. 
it was like they drank the kool-aid too!! eeeekkkk!!!! it’s not just me!!!!! that genuine happy and positive energy was contagious and that right there is the kind of life you want to catch! right??! to top this off it was brought to my attention i could make extra money and earn free trips doing what i was already doing! ...... sharing what i love!!! (duh that’s what you do💁🏻‍♀️) sharing is caring right!?!! ohhhh myyyy it was a game changer for my whole life! 
i started believing in myself. 
seeing what could be possible for me. 
it was time to level up🙌. scared af but i did it. 
has it been easy - nope. but having a dream and seeing your vision actually happening is crazy amazing!!! #metoo #justadream #depressionsucks #emptynesters #mylife @kwaaks_live
name: Mike & Laura Kwaak

text:
love letter monday
•
“our lives begin to end the day we become silent about things that matter.”
•
my favorite quote from dr. martin luther king jr. i know the depth of this truth as well as i know the sound of my mother’s voice. silence is deadly. for decades, i kept quiet of the traumas i experienced as a child, teenager, and young adult. i stayed silent because the few times i did try to share what happened to me, i learned that sometimes, the way people respond to our wounds hurts more than the wounds themself. it’s one thing to be assaulted by a stranger. to be silenced by someone you love hurts with an altogether sharper intensity.

my silence festered into debilitating anorexia. pain, like anything, is an energy. it has to go somewhere. if silenced, it begins to eat the body and mind from within.

finally, at age 30, i wrote i am yours. in there, i set free all the stories that had gone silenced. by speaking and writing what was once muted, i was able to heal my anorexia and create new levels of authentic closeness, comfort, and honesty with those i love. the energy of the past transformed from pain into poetry. i’m so grateful that poetry now lets me serve my purpose, to help others free their voices.

to you, dear one, who may have stayed silent for years: speak your song. owning the power of our voices lets us move from pain into love, fulfillment, and service. stand in your truth, for yourself, for others. the world will become all the more brighter and braver because of the anthem you hold within. voice after voice after voice is how we rise as a movement of love.

love, reema
•
❤️
•
(image of reema sitting on a flight of stairs, smiling.)
•
#iamyours #reemazaman #memoir #mlkday #drking #intersectionalfeminist #lovelettermonday #mondaymotivation #anorexiarecovery #metoo

text:
happy mlk day!!! let this proud post serve as a memorial and shout out to not only those of color (but those of all colors in the rainbow apart of our great world) who had a dream and persevered to make that dream a reality. you too can do the same. hold your head up and be strong because #alllivesmatter!!!
*
(in order of photos in slide show) *
1.) dr. martin luther king jr - he had a dream for equality for all races of people and today we live that dream #godblessamerica...
*
2.) president barack obama & 1st lady michelle obama - because of mlk and his dream coming to fruition... they were afforded rights. the same rights which allowed them to campaign while they too had a dream & the obama's became the #1stafricanamerican president, #1stafricanamerican 1st lady, #1stafricanamerican 1st family in the #whitehouse !
*
3.) vanessa williams - because of mlk's dream, she was afford the opportunity to rights. the same rights which allowed her a chance to compete in their prestigious contest with a dream to become the next #missamerica, despite being dethroned unfairly but was issued an apology by the #missamericaorganization in the #metoo era, she was rightfully crowned as the #1stblackmissamerica a few years back; thus making ways for black females in pageantry!
*
4.) shana e. shaw - because of mlk's dream, i was afforded the opportunity to rights. the same rights which allowed me to found & sit on the board of the non-profit:  shana e. international scholarship program & productions, inc. (official producers of #missinfinity international pageants) *
*
5.) kendrea mcvadon - because of the opportunities #missinfinity offers for all women, she had a dream to become the next #msinfinityinternational #msinfinity #queen #letsgo and she has served and is serving as the #1stafricanamerican #msinfinityamerica & #msinfinityinternational
*
in these hard times of vocalizations being echoed by the collective of people in support of certain national leaders of the usa who's sole purpose is to spread hate, degradation, separation, division, & racism, we must remember that together we stand but divided we fall. #alllivesmatter #ingodwetrust #happymlkday #riseup #riseabovehate

text:
"the arc of the moral universe is long, but it bends towards justice." -mlk jr 
we were too tired to march on saturday. we were worried about being cold like last year. it was hard to see and feel the impact of the marches from the past two years. i whined and created reason upon reason in my head not to go. but we did it. got up early. made signs. and we marched. we marched because it is a privilege. because we taught our children to resist. because we had conversations along the way about usa gymnastics, #metoo, and what intersectionality means - especially to emi and i as women of color. this mlk quote has always been my favorite, maybe mostly because it's so so hard to appreciate in real time. but, we will continue to show up. because we stand on the shoulders of so many who showed up before us, when the risk was much much greater, and the price was too often the ultimate price. thank you #martinlutherkingjr - thank you teaching us to show up.

text:
souvent, on parle pour ne rien dire, de la météo, du jean's ou de la robe qui nous fait de l'oeil en vitrine... blabla... jusque quand les mots manquent, par la force des circonstances et sous le poids des épreuves.
*
melinda a 15 ans, l'âge de l'insouciance, des découvertes, des premiers frissons et des ivresses, des fêtes. pourtant, en quelques secondes d'une #party, tout a changé, le cauchemar a plombé le rêve et les ailes.
*
harcelée, dévalorisée, recroquevillée dans un réduit, murée dans son #silence, la chute est sans fin. que s'est-il passé pour qu'elle en arrive là? ce qui est arrivé à bien plus de personnes qu'on ne croyait. du moins avant #metoo .
*
un #viol, très probablement, mais la question n'est plus là, c'est comment en réchappe-t-on, des semaines, des mois voire des années après l'#agression ? question cruciale pour laquelle la #victime ne peut compter principalement que sur elle-même.
*
speak, c'est le titre de ce #graphicnovel, le symbole, la délivrance encore lointaine puisqu'il faudra un pavé de près de 400 planches pour y arriver. un pavé dans la marre des égoïsmes et du chacun pour soi. une course à la vie à la mort, plus souvent à reculons que vers l'avant.
*
dans les mots de #lauriehalseanderson , #emilycarroll investit personnellement le lecteur par la voie du #journalintime et du #je, avec des scènes en communauté mais toujours le reflet de l'intériorité, sa force et son emprise. être seul avec soi-même.
*
ça fait son effet mais encore faut-il tenir la longueur. carroll, spécialiste de l'horreur, réussit son incursion dans le drame en faisant ce qu'elle fait de mieux, des ombres et de la lumière, des métaphores, de la noirceur surtout. il faut une idée à chaque page, et ça ne s'essouffle.
*
speak, c'est un souffle de mort au bout duquel surgira peut-être celui de la vie, du mot qui libère.
*
#review par @alexc7s
*
#speak, récit complet, @emilyterrible , d'après @halseanderson , traduit par @fanny_soubiran , chez @ruedesevresbd , 384p., 20€.
*
#lecture #nightmare  #rape #woman #harrassment #books #bookstagram #booklover #reader #bibliophile #drama #balancetonporc #bandedessinee #livre @s.levens_agent_litteraire #shout #abuse

text:
trigger warning: rape / pedophilia 
tell it moms is a secret group of ghanaian women. the group peddles a “women’s empowerment” theme while actively hiding the identities of women in the group who cover up for their partners in stories like this. stories like this aren’t rare in the group. there are many cases of marital rape, pedophilia and physical abuse against domestic workers, sister in laws, cousins, etc. sent to the admin of the group day in and day out. however, we think it’s time the ghana police ghana police service bureau of national investigation,  started compelling admins of the group to reveal the identities of members who are involved and complicit in stories such as this. these wives and girlfriends are the accomplices in the most heinous stories, yet somehow nobody seems to be taking notice. where is the ministry of gender? a group as big as this should not be flying under the radar with the sort of abuse shared there daily. where is dovvsu? what is the cyber unit of the ghana police service doing? who speaks up for the helpless in our nation? who defies the culture of silence and reports predators? at some point, we must stop letting these people hide under the guise of anonymity, and start naming and shaming perpetrators and all those complicit in the cover up of the abuse of the women and children of this nation.

text: as i’m sitting here on a beautiful monday at home with my kiddos - i’m feeling incredibly thankful that i took a chance... thankful that i looked past the negative comments and assumptions about network marketing from the uninformed.. thankful that i put my past situations behind me and grew from and above them. thankful that i found my voice and passion in young living.. this company and these products have brought me so much purpose, health and joy. not only that, but i love my job, i get to be home with my kids while i do it and be paid a full time income... if you’re looking for something different.. if you’re missing your kiddos... if you’re tired of living pay cheque to pay cheque and living for the weekends.. if you would rather have a say when you get to work and take time off rather than be controlled by a boss.. if you’d love to have the opportunity to make as much income as you’d like and deserve... if you’re looking for a sense of community while improving your health... (and so much more) this is it. put fear of judgement aside. you’ll be judged no matter what you do. time is our only limited commodity. once it’s gone we can’t get it back. so often i hear mother’s wishing they could stay home with there kids... there is a way you can be home with your babies. please put those fears of being judged, your limiting beliefs about yourself, and the fear of sounding “salesy” aside! it is so far from being salesy. i have received some of the most genuine testimonies of how these products, this income and personal growth has completely transformed people’s lives for the better. their health. their financial situation. their mindset. i get messages from people thanking me for showing them this lifestyle. i want you to have that too! if you’ve been looking and praying for a sign - this is it. 👋🏻 you can help make a massive and positive difference in people’s lives and i’d love to help you. ❤️ there’s a reason i call my team ‘essentially changing lives.’ because all 700 of us are. you only get this one life. stop wishing it was different and make it different. make it count. jump in. it’s worth it. - lauren x

text:
senaste nytt i verklighetens milenniumtrilogi (ska förklara så pedagogiskt jag kan pga detta är rörigt och man kan på många vis inte riktigt tro att det sker i ”rättssäkra sverige”) here we go:
jag anmäler en våldtäkt, det skrivs av, som det nästan alltid gör. sen berättar jag öppet vem som våldtagit mig, främst för att varna för en farlig återfallsförbrytare som så oerhört många skyddat och ännu skyddar. han anmäler mig för grovt förtal. en åklagare plockar upp detta under allmänt åtal, alltså så skattebetalarna står för notan. jag och min advokat ber om att få styrka min berättelse, och mina skäl till varför jag berättat detta. bland annat genom att visa den internutredning mannens egen arbetsplats gjorde hösten 2017, där han pekas ut som sexualbrottsling av flertalet andra personer. förhör ska hållas med denne internutedare nästa vecka, hos polisen där min advokat även är med. men jag fick detta👆 på posten nyligen. åklagaren menar alltså att jag kommer åtalas för grovt förtal, trots att hon ännu inte fått in alla handlingar (bla förhöret med internutredaren). min våldtäktsmans advokat har även lyckats ta sig in på detta förhör med internutredaren, där namn på kvinnor som i förtroende berättat om övergrepp troligtvis kommer komma upp. vi vet att advokaten tidigare ringt upp just sexbrottsutsatta kvinnor på ett högst oetiskt vis.
detta är alltså vad som sker just nu. hur mycket skattepengar kalaset kostat hittills? en miljon? för att tysta och foga en kvinna som lägger skulden och skammen där den hör hemma, visar på en farlig rikskänd ulv i fårakläder. jag funderar på att trycka en t-shirt och bära på rättegången. den ska ha texten ”brott: våldtagen”.(ang det som står först i brevet: enda som är nedlagt är alltså nya anmälningar som kommit in från andra parten, för att jag fortsätter prata öppet om allt som sker, dvs nyttjar mina demokratiska rättigheter) #metoo #handmaidstale

text:
🚨body positive post🚨
"goddis apprecition." 13 mondays ago:
"i'm tired of this body. i'm tired of this life today...this life and body associated with trauma and disruption. i'm tired of being confused and uncertain in this mind. i'm tired working hard to appear okay. i'm tired of having to apologize for my actions because my mind lies to me and tells me i'm in danger when i'm not so i lash out prematurely and over react. i'm tired of second guessing my thoughts, my intentions, my value, and my purpose in the world. i'm tried of defending myself and struggling to accept the good things about my life. i'm tired of doubting the good things and good people around me. i'm just so tired today. if i could take just a 5 minute break from living and breathing in this body and having to be strong enough to live the life aqueela is living, i swear i would. i want to strip my soul (the energy, life force, and subconscious divinity that is truly me, the queen) from this host called aqueela.

ironically, all of this co exists with the belief that i am healing and beautiful and worthy of greatness and purposed, and helpful, and loved and all kinds of wonderful things. i'm just tired of battling both truths." today: i love this body. i love my skin. i love this mind. i love my multi-dimensional experiences and truth. i am a person living with depression & anxiety. i am still a goddis. i am a queen. peace and light.
love, ✊🏼✊🏽✊🏾
📸: brve

text:
last year at the 2018 march for our lives event in washington dc i heard 10 year old yolanda renee king share her dreams for america. as the granddaughter of coretta scott king and martin luther king jr, dreaming big is something that runs through her blood. ⠀
⠀
our country is still far from the world martin dreamed of. some days it feels like we are at a stand still or worse traveling backwards. at times when i feel most fearful for the state of our country, i look at the younger generations. voices like yolanda renee king, mari copeny, an 11 year old activist fighting for clean water in her hometown of flint, michigan, and lane murdock, a 16 year old student from my high school that helped launch the national school walkout movement following the parkland shootings, are the voices that give me the strength to keep going. ⠀
⠀
we tell our children to “think before they speak”, "play nice with others”, and “if you don’t have something nice to say don’t say anything at all", but how often do we as adults hold ourselves to those same standards. maybe it’s time we let the students remind the teachers of the lessons we once preached to them. ⠀
⠀
happy martin luther king jr, coretta scott king, and yolanda renee king day!⠀
⠀

i’m in awe of every person who has pushed out of their comfort zone. who stands up for what they believe in. who makes the world a better place. i’m in gratitude to those who pursue their dreams with no guarantee other than their passion and faith. inspired by those who live to serve and help their communities.
.
these are the factors that guide my life and it’s an honor to be able to see it through communities on ig, through movements like #metoo and to be part of a book called #modelsdoeat to help shift the perception of the female body. it’s what makes me remember that social media can be a powerful tool, when we use to to come together.
.
so today i honor you all. because while yes, it is #martinlutherkingjr day, it’s you who are changing the world each and every day by serving, by loving, by helping, by shining your light to others 💕 #yogainparis #yogabody #parisparis

text:
“el fallecimiento de diana es inexcusable, es cierto. la muerte de una mujer es el dolor de todas y la razón por la que luchamos día a día. y es que la violencia y el machismo no tienen nacionalidad. 
tan sólo en ecuador, el 60,6% de las mujeres ha sufrido algún tipo de violencia, sin distinción entre clase social o nacionalidad. en venezuela, más mujeres mueren por violencia de género que en manos del hampa común, y en latinoamérica en general, cada día mueren asesinadas nueve mujeres.

en el 2017 murieron 2.559 mujeres en manos de la violencia machista en toda la región, y nadie le pidió pasaporte a los agresores. transformar la muerte de una mujer en manos de un hombre en un asunto migratorio es un cinismo tan tajante como decir que la culpa era de ella. 
basta ya de excusar el problema. la muerte de diana no tiene nada que ver con que yordy sea venezolano, sino con que la violencia machista es una epidemia que tiene consumido al continente entero.

http://www.ecuadorencifras.gob.ec/violencia-de-genero/
@leninmorenog 
#ecuador #violenciadegenero #niunamas #metoo #timesup #venezuela #venezolanosenecuador #venezolanosenelmundo #sosvenezuela

text:
bharat mata is a victim of #metoo: chennai’s loyola college art show in major controversy
#
an art festival in chennai's loyola college has triggered a major controversy because a painting was exhibited there with a caption that read: 'bharat mata is a victim of #metoo'.the exhibition also had other paintings with captions like: 'pm modi is a follower of imperialism', 'rss has direct connection with the murder of activist writer gauri lankesh', 'bjp's lotus has turned into rats eating into the rafale deal', among others.the two-day festival--veethi virudhu vizha (street award festival)--was organised from january 19-20. it had an exhibition which was aimed at winning the acme book of world records for the most number of art forms performed under one roof.however, the paintings in the exhibition have not gone down well with some people and a police complaint has already been registered against the college.uma anand, a complainant, said, "the program was called 'street award festival' but it had nothing to do with it. what does street award mean? is it to insult our national symbols? our prime minister? was it organised to degrade everything?"anu chandramouli, a bjp worker, said the loyola college gets grants from the central government through the university grants commission. "it is supposed to be secular in character. but the…

text:
on a day that means so much.  mlk day... my daughter made me a bracelet that means more than she will ever know. 
black and white entangled and intertwined forever.  he had a dream.  we all have a dream.  however some stand by them, but more importantly some stand up for them. 
no other person has the right to bring you down, push you down, or quiet you. 
in the past few days i have gone through one of the most traumatic situations for my life.  one that has changed me forever and transformed my perspective on how people treat other for the rest of my life. 
it is not acceptable to treat people like shit, discriminate, harass, or assault anybody or any reason. even if you don’t think it’s a big deal. 
this nation was founded on the principle that all people are created equal and that everyone has the right to pursue happiness. 
dr. king and many others have fought for this simple and basic right that so many disrespect out of fear, judgment, or ignorance. 
we live in a world that is so simple and would be easy to live in if we just did one thing. 
use empathy and see things from others point of view.  walk in others’ shoes. a little gift from my suz-a-loop.  it’s good to have at least one girl of the 4. 
#daddyanddaughter #mygirl #kidcrafts #braclets #mlk #civilrights #standup #metoo #equalrights

it is not acceptable to treat people like shit, discriminate, harass, or assault anybody or any reason. even if you don’t think it’s a big deal. 
this nation was founded on the principle that all people are created equal and that everyone has the right to pursue happiness. 
dr. king and many others have fought for this simple and basic right that so many disrespect out of fear, judgment, or ignorance. 
we live in a world that is so simple and would be easy to live in if we just did one thing.

text:
“i can and i will. watch me.”
•
•
so it’s mlk day and the women’s march anniversary has been going on all weekend, so this is my little tribute to all those people. the people who decided that they were going to change the world for better. and when they were told that they would never make an impact, that they should just be satisfied, that they should just smile and be happy and calm, they decided to say “screw satisfied, screw nice, screw calm. i’m going to change the world and you can watch me.”
so let’s follow in their footsteps and break the mold. because despite all the things we will hear, this is a world worth fighting for. so let’s fight and change it for the better.
#womensmarch #mlk #metoo #feminist

text:
pipi calzaslargas (galtzaluze/langstrump) enseñó más de feminismo que todas las princesas disney juntas 💪💜🐒 inspiración para todas aquellas que se preguntaban por qué tenían que llevar vestidos cuando era más cómodo correr con pantalones, por qué tenían que pensar en compartir su vida con hombres cuando los caballos (o los gatos, o los perros) les gustaban mucho más. 
pippi rompe con todo lo que consideramos "apropiado" socialmente hablando para una chica: no pide permiso, no pide perdón y, sobre todo, no se somete a los marcados estereotipos de género que tanto daño nos han hecho. carácter indomable

pippi, una joven independiente, feliz, pizpireta, rodeada de animales y cuya preocupación por su apariencia física era nula. ¡una niña feliz! su felicidad no era solo interior, sino también exterior; y es que su ropa le servía precisamente para mostrar toda esta vitalidad, estas ganas de vivir y de ser libre.

no queremos una sirena que se desprenda de sus piernas por conseguir el amor de un hombre, sino una chica con trenzas que se preocupe únicamente por divertirse, ser independiente y valerse por sí misma.
📍texto: los replicantes

text:
it’s been 2019 for a hot second and already i’ve been sexually assaulted more times than i can count on one hand 🖐 
from inappropriate comments, cat calls and even touch!
some strangers and some friends, some who knew better and some who didn’t.
the sad thing about the #metoo movement is it trended and disappeared like a lot issues, on to the next one.
i discovered a lot about the mans perspective during this time. some shared stories, that they knew they had pushed for intimacy that wasn’t fully reciprocated, having to persuade the other. 
they felt bad for it, and so did i...
and in response i learned that women just don’t have the tools. i didn’t and we still don’t. 
the words, the examples, the conversations of not just sharing our tramas, but how to learn from them so it doesn’t happen again.  to identify what is fore play and what is manipulation. 
what is honest feelings of excitement and what is this intuition screening “no you’re not ready”
as a woman, our inution is our most powerful resource. and from a young age we are never taught how to listen to it, how to trust it and let us be guided by it.

when we ignore her and let things ride out we tend to feel guilt after the incident. thinking “i knew i didn’t want to do that, why didn’t i stop them” but being ‘polite’ or worried you won’t be liked seems far more important then being liked by your self.
 it’s 2019 and there is still a lot of work to be done to liberate women, to educate men, to evolve as humans. 
#still #metoo 
if anyone wants to talk, i’m here to listen, really.

text:
this weekend, thousands joined in a women’s march across the world. 80 events across 31 cities saw women protest against violence and systems of oppression.

there were so many amazing signs! so many powerful messages! so many incredible women!

this sign in particular struck a chord. many people believe that change has happened, that equality is in progress but it’s so clear, to so many people that this simply isn’t true. we, as women, are at the start of our journey. we at about times, are just getting started.

#womenswave #womensmarch #wearepowerful #wearewomen #feminist #feminism #metoo #timesup #endviolence #strongwomen #powerfulwomen #womensvoices #bywomenforeveryone #abouttimes

text:
slogans de camisetas podem empoderar! mas não deveriam empoderar a mulher que as fez também?

o @guardian revelou que as camisetas das spice girls com a campanha “justiça de gênero” foram confeccionadas em uma fábrica em bangladesh, onde as mulheres ganham o equivalente a centavos por hora durante os turnos de até 16h/dia em que alegam ser abusadas verbalmente e assediadas. 
onde está o poder feminino nisso?

é muito simples e de vital importância: conheça sua cadeia de suprimentos, pergunte #whomademyclothes se você não consegue ver, não pode consertar, e é por isso que  @fash_rev recomenda que mais marcas e varejistas tenham transparência total na cadeia de suprimentos.
nós vemos a necessidade de maior transparência através do trabalho justo e decente, proteção ambiental e igualdade de gênero como vetores interseccionais que moldarão o futuro da moda, a fim de entender melhor como alcançar uma mudança positiva na indústria global da moda.

post da maravilhosa @carrysomers do @fash_rev ❤️ #fashrev #girlpower #genderjustice #metoo

slogans de camisetas podem empoderar! mas não deveriam empoderar a mulher que as fez também?

o  revelou que as camisetas das spice girls com a campanha “justiça de gênero” foram confeccionadas em uma fábrica em bangladesh, onde as mulheres ganham o equivalente a centavos por hora durante os turnos de até 16h/dia em que alegam ser abusadas verbalmente e assediadas. 
onde está o poder feminino nisso?

é muito simples e de vital impoância: conheça sua cadeia de suprimentos, pergunte  se você não consegue ver, não pode consear, e é por isso que   recomenda que mais marcas e varejistas tenham transparência total na cadeia de suprimentos.
nós vemos a necessidade de maior transparência através do trabalho justo e decente, proteção ambiental e igualdade de gênero como vetores interseccionais que moldarão o futuro da moda, a fim de entender melhor como alcançar uma mudança positiva na indústria global da moda.

post da maravilhosa  do  ❤️

text: molestowanie uliczne - w polsce niewiele się o tym mówi, a praktycznie prawie nic. molestowanie to nie tylko dotyk, ale też słowo. wulgarne komentarze, gwizdanie, cmokanie, czy gesty to również molestowanie. w polsce wbrew pozorom molestowanie uliczne wcale nie należy do rzadkości. sama byłam w sytuacji gdy dwóch kolegów idących ulicą mówili chamskie komentarze na mój temat. komentarze pokroju "ale masz fajną dupeczkę", "takiej to bym z łóżka nie wyrzucił", "ale ma brzydkie obwisłe cyce", "płaska jak deska" to molestowanie seksualne, tylko że słowne. mamy prawo czuć się niekomfortowo w obliczu takich sytuacji. #feminizm #feminism #feministka #feminist #proudfeminist #molestowanieseksualne #metoo #jateż

text:
@bozarbrussels hosted a very special author last night and what a satisfying conversation it was!! 😍 it's so rare nowadays to come across writers who can be best described as "intellectual centipedes" 🐛🐛(i didn't invent that one, unfortunately). ian buruma is definitely one of them! from japanese soft porn to the problem of islamic extremism in the netherlands, through analyses of the 1st and 2nd world wars, touching upon the problematic of jewish immigration and assimilation in the uk, he writes non-fiction books that read better than fiction... we even managed to talk about #metoo and brexit, running a bit behind the schedule though 😋. cherry on the pie, i got my book signed by the author! #groupie mode on 🤣 .
.
.
p.s. since today is #bluemonday and everyone is crying their eyes out because of abandoned ny resolutions, counting the days to the very far summer holidays (according to the mainstream media), i will join the regretful crowd and admit that i was not supposed to buy books in q1 and so badly failed!!!! now i'm waiting for my depression to kick in 🤣...

so believers is performing it's next activity in master ayub's school. master ayub is a philanthropist, civil servant and an educator who took an initiative in 1986 to start a free school for those underprivileged children who could not afford education

text:
week 3: #twft52 
i have thought about this in many ways over the years, as i learned to come to terms with my introverted nature. i often wonder if i’m introverted because of or whether in spite of it all i would have been introverted nonetheless.
.
i am glad for the way this prompt organized some of the mess of thoughts and feelings i experience when i try to articulate the difference between the moments i enjoy my solitude and the times when it feels like it’s swallowing me whole.
.
with practice and time, i hope one day it will always or mostly be an enjoyable and voluntary solitude. i have really come to value my alone time though i’m still working on balancing that with a healthy amount of social time..
.
.
.
.
.
#intjfemale #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #anxiety #depression #endthestigma #metoo #ibelieveher #progressnotperfection #nyc #bekind

text:
feeling entergetically light and clear today after last nights full moon eclipse. 
as an empath and clairvoyant, i carry the responsibility of clearing energies for the collective- including myself. during harsh planetary alighnments i feel myself intutivley turn within and prepair my mind, body and spirit for transmutation of the collective energies (sometimes falling off the map altogether) 
this year i felt the freeing energy of the woman involved in the #metoo movement, those who are feeling the burden of the government shutdown, and refugees who are waiting for clearance within a defaulted system. i'm honored to assist with the awakening of humanity on an molecular scale and i feel the weight lifting from us all- including myself in a big way this year. 
old behaviors, old belief systems, old paradighms, relationships, residence, and jobs that are no longer serving us are being released on a mass scale. i'm honored to witness and be apart of the biggest entergetic shift humanity has ever witnessed in this lifetime.

some will be left behind and others will move and integrate unto the vehicle of spiritual and biological evolution.

we are not in the clear yet! however harnessing awareness, understanding, having compassion and unconditional love, practicing non judgment and forgiveness and gaining knowledge and understanding during this time is imperative. rest, internalize, process, and use this time for deep healing as we move into 4th dimensional energies in 2019. 
great work everyone!

text:
i’m a secret nerd for research and i did my part as a participant yesterday and took my quarterly survey for the nurses’ health study. the interesting thing, it also brought up a lot of stuff for me that i haven’t had to think about in quite a while.
.
i’m used to answering questions about basic health metrics and pregnancy... i’m not used to answering questions about abuse. familial, domestic, romantic, stranger... especially back to my pre-“adult” life.
.
got heavy fast, huh?
.
you see, i grew up in a home with domestic violence towards my mom and my brothers, and a lot of yelling towards everyone. i dated a handful of shitty guys before i met my incredibly respectful and integrity filled husband. i struggled with depression, i still suffer occasional anxiety attacks, and i don’t need to walk down the #metoo storyline right now, but that happened too.
.
you see, when i see or meet a resilient, strong person, i wonder what they rose above because i believe we are all survivors of something.
.
your story is powerful, unique, and beautifully broken. you are the amazing person you are because of the earthquakes you weathered.
.
you are not worth less because of the trauma you experienced. you are strong af for still showing up and pressing on.
.
and please, don’t forget, there is always someone who can listen, help or provide you with resources. you are enough and i will
celebrate and honor your strength. ❤️
.
.
child abuse: 1-800-422-4453
domestic violence: 1-800–799-7233
sexual assault: 1-800-656-4673
suicide prevention: 1-800-273-talk (8255)
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#madeformore #iamasurvivor #strongaf #strongasamother #postpartumdepression #riseup #transformyourlife #neveralone #motivationmonday

text:
my mission and goal is to teach women how to believe in themselves,care for themselves, balance the curve balls life throws, and follow their dreams.
.
after 20+ years working in the behavioral health field specializing in eating disorders, self-injury, & suicide prevention, i transitioned to coaching women to learn to love themselves, live their lives and follow their dreams. 
you might pause and think “oh wow! that’s some serious topics” and that you don’t relate.  but underlying all of that is a lack of self-worth, not feeling worthy/special, feeling less than, wishing you could feel better about yourself, a wanting to live your dreams.  if you are wanting to learn to like yourself, that is something i can help you with!  let’s connect - click on the link in my bio (@denisestyer) so we can connect 💜

text:
black mass week 7 day 4: max day
body weight: 220
squat: 475
bench: 375
deadlift: 425

today we tested our 1 rms for the next phase of the mass program starting a week from monday, which calls for 65-75% work rates. these numbers are far from lifetime prs, but my mobility/rom as well as endurance and work capacity has shot through the roof. a lot of people hang numbers in the gym over their heads which leads them to getting injured, setbacks, and attempting ego lifts. news flash: unless you’re a powerlifter/weightlifter, it doesn’t fucking matter, loser. be comfortable with who you are and what you’re capable of. you’ve got some deeper-seeded issues if that’s your reasoning for training. we chase movement, not numbers, cause who gives a shit.

thanks for supporting and pushing me through this program @james_benedix @tremily_ and @clintonious_ so proud of my team.

#worksmarter #bebetter #mobile #agile #hostile #effort #strength #progress #blackmass #mass #maximumeffort #team #squad #dothework #discipline

text:
plot twist! you are the bag! secure yourselves!
—-
i didn’t grow up in a big house with fancy cars & designer clothes. my mom raised my two sisters and i alone♥️we didn’t grow up with the latest labels.
there were no family ski vacations 
having “college paid for by your single mom” wasn’t really an option🤫🤣 i will share with you what we did have🤗😮!!!
___

warm beds 🛌 in a spotless home.
fresh homemade homegrown food at my grandmas house 🏡 a plethora of lessons i don’t think my mother had a clue she was teaching! protection and friendship of my two older sisters. a bond with our precious grandmother la golda who was (& still is in heaven) an absolute saint! a mentally disabled next door neighbor named jenny who i had the opportunity to call my best friend♥️a huge 🌲tree on the side of the house to climb every night. bicycle’s and neighborhood friends to catch lightning bugs (we set them free). home popped popcorn made by my mom while watching reruns of dallas & falcon crest. my mom always pointing out the goodness of bobbi over jr🍿🍿😮!!!
____

we always had animals. from fish to cats & dogs. my mom didn’t spoil us...she couldn’t! she taught us instead. not by instruction but by example. she is a genuine, funny, beautiful hard working woman. she loved us with an open heart and never withheld affection.
we went to good schools
we got plenty of hugs 
we were loved dearly by our mom, grandma, aunts, uncles & cousins. 
____

we all worked throughout high school at a local mall. i’m almost certain each of us began working there by the age of 15. my sister cassandra managed a shoe store,  my sister stacey was a makeup artist in a department store & i worked in a men’s clothing store for four years. we were not brought up to be lazy. we worked! 
___

there was a time in my life where i became temporarily dependent on another & vice verse. this was the weakest time of my life. a time where my self esteem went from high to non existent🤫🤨😞one day i woke up & remembered who’s daughter i was. i straitened my crown & got my a** back to work. 
if you are in a codependent situation i suggest you create a plan & begin depending on yourself. ⤵️continue

text:
少しのあいだ、utakomurofutureringanimal1は
ソロ出演です☆

例えばの一例ですが、技術以外のコト🌿

音楽や芸能のコトで私も歳上でありながら、恥ずかしくも言葉正しく、男の子に穏やかに注意するコトが出来ず、厳しく注意をしてしまったり😵

スタジオドラムセットにぶつかり、倒れかけたりとかあった場合…😧 相手が怒ってるときでも楽器を大切にする気持ち＝敬意を忘れてほしくないので、すぐに元通りにさせて私ではなく、
楽器に謝って頂いたり🙏🏻🌿💦 一例ではありますが、そんな事でも少し自粛して頂いています🙏🏻🌿 若ければ、男の子の仲間同士なら許されるかも知れません。が

好きなミュージシャンと対バン出来ない、大好きな音楽が自由に出来ない時間は、気の毒にも感じます🌱 
それでも #metoo 性暴力 防止に繋げる活動＝タレント＝小室うた。
他にもいろいろな意味合いで活動しています🌏

その作曲を担当しているコトに誇りを持って頂けるように、私もバナナの皮にすっ転びながらもコツコツ歩み続けます🌿🍌 まだまだヒヨコでぴよぴよと不思議の国の住民になりがちですが😳宇宙人❓

ただの変人？から芸術が死ぬまでに少しでも上達できたら幸いです🌿

今日も朝まで深夜練習〜

お腹空いてねむい😵💤頑張ろうー

焼肉食べたい😳、、節約しなくては🌏

追伸

偏屈なのは年齢800歳だからかもです㊙︎
🌿

text:
artists and activists bring attention to injustice. they inspire us with their images and words, and they give us courage to enact change in our own spheres of life. they lead with bold defiance and they change society’s priorities by creating new story lines for history. they are our heroes.
💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
activist heroes do not bring about change alone, though. everyday people who go about their business of doing what they do against a backdrop of societal chaos are the most important change makers in our world.
💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
a woman came into my studio a couple of weeks ago, and we struck up a conversation about my “me too - pain to power” artwork that i am working on. she was much younger than me. she told me that she was a welder working in a shop with mostly male coworkers. since her start at the shop, however, other women have been hired, and their presence has brought considerable positive change to the workplace. safety has improved and managers have become more effective and efficient. there is now a program to encourage and train women to become welders at the shop. she is a critical part of that program.
💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
she shared that it bothers her when people say she is doing a man’s job. “i’m a woman, and this is my job,” she said. 💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
as we closed the conversation, she thanked me for bringing attention to women’s issues with my art. i  was instantly humbled and i felt sort of remiss. she was the one bringing real change on the front lines of feminism just by doing what she does. i should be thanking her.
💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
i did thank her. 💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
on this day that we celebrate one the greatest activist heroes of all time, i celebrate the everyday heroes who do the frontline change of just doing what they do. artists and activists give us images and narratives for a movement for change, but everyday people make it real. 💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
if that’s you, i celebrate you.
💪🏿💪🏽💪🏻
please share a story in the comments about someone that you know who is bringing about change in his or her sphere of life just by doing what they do.  #activism #everydayheroes #martinlutherkingjr #mlkday #metoo #movingfrompaintopower #changeismessy

#repost @theglossarymagazine
・・・
the winter issue - the trailblazers leading 2019 💥💥💥💥💥💥💥
cover star model and body positivity activist @charlihoward talks mental health, happiness and why the fashion industry needs to be more diverse. photography by the incredible @desiree_mattsson
make-up by @lindawickmann —————————————————————
elsewhere in the issue:
keira knightley on playing the maverick 20th century-writer sidonie-gabrielle in the biopic colette. the actress also tells us how motherhood informs her choices and what’s next for #metoo
christian dior: designer of dreams curator #oriolecullen gives us an insight into the forthcoming @vamuseum exhibition and pays homage to the french couturier and the house of @dior.
inspirational design duo @bella_freud and @retrouvius founder maria speake share the vision behind their recent collaboration, a 1970s styled penthouse @thisistvc in white city.
restaurant stars ollie dabbous, yevgeny chichvarkin and tatiana fokina of @hedonism_wines, and oskar kinberg - the wunderteam behind mayfair’s hugely-successful @hide_restaurant - let us into their plans for 2019; plus it’s cocktail o’clock at the capital’s newest openings, and hilary armstrong reviews the capital’s finest indian restaurants.
fashion writer @hilaryalexanderobe explores the enduring allure of leopard print, plus watch connoisseur @mingliuwrites reports back from the exclusive launch of the new @patekphilippe twenty~4 automatic, and we edit the ultimate diamond pieces that will add dazzle to any wrist. 
renowned yogi, wellness entrepreneur and go-to holistic guru @juliemontagu reveals her secrets to a healthy and happy life, and london’s foremost sleep experts give their tips on how to get a better night’s sleep 💤

and as always, we bring you the inside track on all the don’t-miss cultural & arts events across the capital. link in bio and available to buy in all good newsagents 📖
#theglossary #theglossarymagazine #charlihoward #misfit #bodypositivity #keiraknightley #christiandior #dior #bellafreud #olliedabbous #londonlife #whatsoninlondon

text:
on this glorious and quite historic day, i would like to say thank you to all those who came before me and pray for all those who will come after me. the fight for equality, equity, fairness, and love has never and will never be easy but we continue to do it because we know that all people are deserving of love regardless of race, gender, religion, ethnicity, nationality, socio-economic status, sexual orientation, or disability. 
so, to celebrate mlk jr., i applaud all people who are fighting for immigrant and refugee rights, women's rights, the blm movement against police brutality, against systemic racism, against poverty, #metoo, gun reform, #marchforourlives, against ecological devastation, criminal justice and prison reform, against the alt right, and against the racism, prejudice, and discrimination against poc, muslims, jews, and native americans in this country and beyond. change starts at home and it starts by saying no to our current president, donald j trump and all those in the world who do not believe that "maga" and "build that wall" are rooted in racism and white supremacy :) mlk jr. did not just teach an ethic of love, but empowered people and led the fight against injustice specifically targeted against militarism, poverty, and racism. if you're unwilling to recognize that mlk was a martyr, murdered for fighting not for a change in people's vernacular but for a revolution in america and the world, please do not quote this man and attempt to use him as political tool to advance and perpetuate your own racism. 
43% of the people in this country are poor. everyone loves dead prophets but are you willing to act? racism and injustice is rooted in policy. until we stop compromising on what is clearly right and wrong and start treating everyone with the dignity they deserve, we will not be a great nation. 
our country's, and the world's, history is something to be remembered so that we can battle it everyday. don't erase it, embrace and use it to fuel the change we will bring in the future. 
that's the conclusion of my ted talk, hope you learned something.
name: Ginika Nwaba
tweet_full:
on this glorious and quite historic day, i would like to say thank you to all those who came before me and pray for all those who will come after me. the fight for equality, equity, fairness, and love has never and will never be easy but we continue to do it because we know that all people are deserving of love regardless of race, gender, religion, ethnicity, nationality, socio-economic status, sexual orientation, or disability. 
so, to celebrate mlk jr., i applaud all people who are fighting for immigrant and refugee rights, women's rights, the blm movement against police brutality, against systemic racism, against poverty, #metoo, gun reform, #marchforourlives, against ecological devastation, criminal justice and prison reform, against the alt right, and against the racism, prejudice, and discrimination against poc, muslims, jews, and native americans in this country and beyond. change starts at home and it starts by saying no to our current president, donald j trump and all those in the world who do not believe that "maga" and "build that wall" are rooted in racism and white supremacy :) mlk jr. did not just teach an ethic of love, but empowered people and led the fight against injustice specifically targeted against militarism, poverty, and racism. if you are unwilling to recognize that mlk was a martyr, murdered for fighting not for a change in people's vernacular but for a revolution in america and the world, please do not quote this man and attempt to use him as political tool to advance and perpetuate your own racism. 
43% of the people in this country are poor. everyone loves dead prophets but are you willing to act? racism and injustice is rooted in policy. until we stop compromising on what is clearly right and wrong and start treating everyone with the dignity they deserve, we will not be a great nation. 
our country's, and the world's, history is something to be remembered so that we can battle it everyday. do not erase it, embrace and use it to fuel the change we will bring in the future. 
that's the conclusion of my ted talk, hope you learned something.

text:
“when i was in elementary school i would always see everyone call each other pretty and beautiful but no one said it to me yea your parents say but truly you think your just saying that i'm your kid i'm middle school it got worse everyone would say i'm ugly and fat so being the preteen i was i would believe everyday in the morning and after school i would lock myself in the bathroom and just stare at myself calling my self ugly and fat i was never confident in what i wore or talking to people

and with having little confidence in myself i wouldn't talk to people when people where behind me laughing i would be afraid they were laughing at me in highschool freshman year it was the same but i thought maybe if i tear others girls down people will like be and call me beautiful so i did and realized it was helping me with anything 10th grade year i became extremely depressed to wear i didn't want to be around anymore so i didn't go to school for awhile and tried to find my inner peace

throughout my 10th grade year i realized that i was beautiful it took me so long to realize that bow being a junior in highschool i'm very aware that i'm a beautiful and amazing individual i really appreciate my experience throughout my life it taught me that i should truly love myself the way god or whom every created me”

text:
yesterday the guardian revealed that the spice girls #iwannabeaspicegirl comic relief 'gender justice' t-shirts were made  in a factory in bangladesh where women earn 35p an hour during shifts in which they claim to be verbally abused and harassed. where's the girl power in that?

it's very simple and of vital importance: know your supply chain, ask #whomademyclothes  if you can’t see it, you can’t fix it, which is why fashion revolution urges more brands and retailers to have full supply chain transparency. 
we see the need for greater transparency across fair and decent work, environmental protection and gender equality as intersectional drivers that will shape the future of fashion in order to better understand how to achieve positive change in the global fashion industry. 
we urge any celebrity, charity or cause to first do their homework to ensure that their garment is sourced from a supply chain where all workers are paid decent wages and operate in safe, healthy conditions.
#girlpower #feminism #empowerment #genderjustice #fashionrevolution

text:
http://ow.ly/um1t30noai0
a couple weeks ago, i was groped by a stranger at a bar. this is a pretty normal occurrence, but the fact that this happened while i was surrounded by large, protective male friends and next to my best friend (who was also groped) made me take pause. why did i freeze? what does my response mean about the person i thought i was? about the fight for gender equality? for my thoughts, click the link above. feel free to read my article and, if you feel inclined, comment there with your own thoughts or experiences.

@dr.annakaminska
www.breakingtheglassceiling.coach

there is strong evidence that confidence is more important than ability 
when it comes to getting ahead, and success correlates more closely with 
confidence than it does with competence. countless studies confirm that 
compared with men, women do not consider themselves ready for promotion, 
they feel that they do worse on tests, and they do not feel confident at 
their jobs.

the way we feel and think today is the aftermath of the roles and 
positions women have had for thousands of years. for centuries, our 
cultures, societies, and religions have been perpetuating rooted 
patterns of emotional reactions, while simultaneously suppressing our 
feminine power. we were programmed to be powerless and subordinate.

in order to become a self-confident, powerful woman you need to change 
the chemistry of your brain and become a new kind of person on a 
biological level. you need to reprogram your outdated thinking patterns. 
neuroscience gives us effective tools to transform. are you ready to 
transform?

text:
www.breakingtheglassceiling.coach

there is strong evidence that confidence is more important than ability 
when it comes to getting ahead, and success correlates more closely with 
confidence than it does with competence. countless studies confirm that 
compared with men, women do not consider themselves ready for promotion, 
they feel that they do worse on tests, and they do not feel confident at 
their jobs.

the way we feel and think today is the aftermath of the roles and 
positions women have had for thousands of years. for centuries, our 
cultures, societies, and religions have been perpetuating rooted 
patterns of emotional reactions, while simultaneously suppressing our 
feminine power. we were programmed to be powerless and subordinate.

in order to become a self-confident, powerful woman you need to change 
the chemistry of your brain and become a new kind of person on a 
biological level. you need to reprogram your outdated thinking patterns. 
neuroscience gives us effective tools to transform. are you ready to 
transform?

text:
« parole de féministe » est la concrétisation d’une idée que j’ai depuis plusieurs mois. féministe depuis aussi longtemps que je me souvienne, je voulais prendre la parole et mêler ma passion de l’écriture à mon intérêt pour les droits des femmes. c’est ainsi qu’est apparu, il y a quelques jours, un padlet, sorte de blog où je publie et partage mes idées féministes. certains textes sont légers, humouristiques, sarcastiques, d’autres sont plus sérieux, d’autres davantage chargés d’émotion. ils s’adressent aux femmes comme aux hommes, dans l’espoir d’expliquer ce qu’est le féminisme, et pourquoi c’est essentiel.
💥 le lien du padlet est dans la bio et ici: https://padlet.com/aurore_lentz/paroledefeministe
je posterai sur ce compte des extraits des textes publiés.
si toi aussi tu es féministe jusqu’au bout des lèvres, ou si tu souhaites le devenir, ou juste en apprendre plus, bienvenue ! 🌈

•
•
•

text:
i've had this picture saved to my phone for almost five years now. this used to be me.
.
about five years ago, i went through one of the most traumatic experiences of my life. but i didn't tell anybody. not my friends, my family, my wonderful roommate, my professors or classmates. not even my best friend since the beginning of high school. because i felt like telling them something so horrific would become a burden on them. so i kept it to myself, and let it eat away at me for years. it wasn't until i finally realized that i was so broken that i no longer even cared about the social stigma of people who went to therapy. i went. and i am forever grateful to myself for doing so.
.
ever since then, i've been committed to being more open about my struggles and problems. i turn to my best friends now when i can't cope, because i know they'll be there to catch me, just like i will always be for them. and they will never, ever be a burden on me.
.
if you need an ear, i will do my best to be here for you, as well. my inbox is always open. 💖
.
.
.
#toxic #toxictraits #burden #problems #therapy #talktome #hereforyou #friends #struggle #support #supportyourfriends #positivity #positivevibes #itgetsbetter #metoo #timesup #mentalhealth

text:
sometimes i struggle with staying positive and remembering how good humanity can really be. this was the reminder i needed to reinstill my optimistic outlook. it's so easy to get caught up in the negative, but yesterday i saw people from all walks of life come together to show their belief in equality and their willingness to fight for it. this wasn't only to protect women, but to protect our environment, embrace intersectional feminism, and artistically express the value of diversity. i feel reenergized and excited to keep standing up for what i believe in. i am pretty thankful to have these good people by my side.💕😊
.
.
.

a bend in the penis is totally normal. some penises curve slightly to the left or right, while others may curve upward or downward when it's erect. but if you have a more significant bend in your penis, which may cause you pain or difficulty having sex, see your general practitioner (gp) or go to your local genitourinary medicine (gum) clinic. these can sometimes be symptoms of peyronie's disease. 
peyronie's disease causes the penis to become curved when it's erect. the condition mostly affects men over 40, although it can happen at any age.

the symptoms of peyronie's disease include:

a thickened area or hard lump (plaque) in the shaft of the penis (it's rare to get more than one plaque)

a curve in the penis when it's erect (usually it curves upwards)

pain in the penis, usually during an erection (pain in the non-erect penis is rare)

the penis looking misshapen, like an hourglass

loss of length or girth of the penis 
some men with the condition get pain in their penis, while others get none. if you do get pain, it may get better over time.
but in severe cases, the curve in the penis can make having sex difficult, painful or even impossible. peyronie's disease may also lead to erectile dysfunction. .
.

text:
below are answers to the most common questions i've been getting about my reclaiming radiance program:
⠀⠀
✨the focus is purely on where you are now and where you want to be, not the past. yes, you will be digging deep into the roots of your vritis (mind disturbances), but i will not ask you probing questions that may prompt you to relive your past.
⠀⠀
✨there is no such thing as a norm or accepted standard for experiencing trauma. you do not need to convince me that your your story and your feelings are valid or worthy of healing. i believe you and i know you deserve to live a life filled with contentment, vulnerability, and ultimate bliss. all are welcome to join in this healing process!
⠀⠀
✨this program is designed to work in parallel with your therapist, not replace it. ⠀⠀
✨there is a structure to the program in order to make sure that i'm able to give you all the tools that i have in a timely manner, however this program is very customizable to your needs
⠀⠀
number 1 question: "do you really believe you can heal after trauma?":
✨yes, i 100% believe you can heal after trauma. is that the same thing as being cured? no. healing is a transformative process where you dig within and the path leads you to your highest self. curing is a quick fix that removes all problems and brings you back to "normal". there is no such thing as a quick fix with trauma and i'd bet that you'd prefer growth and radiance over being "normal" or back to the old you. i built this program from my personal experience and i can tell you first hand that growth is dirty, rewarding, and oh so beautiful all in one!

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this is something that i really needed to see today. 
i've been struggling a lot lately with my thoughts and really feeling nervous about my upcoming trial against my perpetrator. they have fought so hard to try to keep me quiet for what feels like an eternity. the stunts they've pulled have all been an attempt to make me give up, to make me feel that no one will believe me. but the truth is that i have so many people on my side who do believe me, that my attackers only chance at getting away with this, is to try to continue making me feel powerless.
•
and my attacker has made me feel powerless; for what they did to me and for what they still do to me in my recurrent nightmares and my flashbacks. they have made me feel powerless in more ways than i can count and in ways that no amount of words can quite describe. they've continued ripping me apart, much like they did when they attacked me, only now it's all mentally, though i swear i still feel it physically.
•
but this, this quote right here reminded me that i am not powerless. 
in fact, i am powerful. 
i am strong because i have refused to give up, no matter how hard they've tried to make me keep my mouth shut. they've tried to make me stay silent because they are afraid of the consequences they will have to live with if the truth i tell is believed by those i testify in front of. 
the truth is that they are afraid of my voice.
and they should be.
because i am going to stand and testify. i know that i cannot change the wrong that was done to me, but i'll be damned if i don't try my hardest to ensure that this monster does not do to others what he did to me. 
and for that, i will tell my story.
•
they can try to keep me silent, to keep me from telling the truth. 
but i will not be silent. 
i will shout if i must.
i will tell the truth.
•
i am strong.
i am resilient.

text:
the term “toxic masculinity” keeps finding its way into social media threads and now even advertisements (we all know that new gillette ad - we believe). this term is widely misconstrued to mean masculinity is bad or toxic, which really misses the point. masculinity as well as femininity are not inherently good or bad and much of how we define gender is actually more of a result of deeply ingrained social constructs.

i felt compelled to write about this because it shows up in my therapy office. 
check out my latest blog in the bio to read more ⬆️⬆️
.
.
.

helen and i were asked to write for this month’s full moon issue of roar, feminine rising online magazine. 
it took alot of strength for me to take this ownership and share what i did. it is very telling and i’m sure judgments will be made. i feel amazing that i have let this piece of my past out, and can continue to move forward. 
head to the website above to purchase the issue for only $4. support this amazing work by women from all over the globe. 
i believe in full expression of one’s self and creativity no matter what others may think. thank you melissa kelly for this opportunity. thank you helen edwards for being my partner and inspiring my wild side. love you both and honored to share this journey with you! 🙏🏼🔥🌟❤️

l o v e people // fight for justice 🚩 this month is human trafficking awareness month, and with over 40 million slaves in the world today, human trafficking is one of the greatest injustices of our lifetime. @lovejusticeintl attacks human trafficking at the most strategic point: while a person is being trafficked and sends them to safety, while at the same time gathering data and arresting and convicting traffickers. 🌟 you can help save a life for just $100, or less than $10 a month. every life is beautiful and worth fighting for. visit the link in my bio (lovejustice.ngo) to learn more. 💫

text:
**full video on the sk1nnyvegan facebook page** this was an interesting interaction.  i started talking with one group when another group stepped in and interjected.

the first group i started doing outreach with took over my job for a brief moment and were giving anti-speciesist talking points to the party late to the conversation.

the party second to the conversation gave a common rebuttal:

what about racism?  what about human rights?

the counter to this extremely simple and straightforward.

we all already oppose racism, sexism, and homophobia.  these forms of discrimination are evil and we oppose all of them simultaneously.

there is no reason we can not add speciesism to thr mix of evils to oppose.

in fact, speciesism is the root form of hatred.  none of the others evils will fall until they all fall.

living in cognitive dissonance land pretending we can care about some sentient beings while we condemn other sentient beings to slavery and death will not make the world a better place.

text:
crisis services statement re new proposed title ix rules #handsoffix
-
proposed title ix regulations: https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/title-ix-nprm.pdf 
submit your comment here: https://www.handsoffix.org/submit-a-comment/
-
full text: in november, the department of education, under secretary devos proposed new title ix regulations that stand to impact student survivors of sexual violence.  the proposed changes narrow the definition of sexual harassment and have the potential to discourage survivors from reporting and seeking help. our communities deserve learning environments free from sexual violence. more than 25% of our population experiences sexual violence. experiencing sexual assault can disrupt student success, leading to poor academic performance, delayed graduation or even withdrawal from school. in the wake of the #metoo movement and the 2011 dear colleague letter, this is regressive legislation that hinders the progress we have made for survivor’s rights on college campuses.

as experts in responding to and preventing sexual assault and domestic violence, we have served our local community for over 40 years. we are proud of our collaborations with k-12 schools and campus communities throughout the county. through our partnerships, including co-location of staff on college campuses, we work to provide direct victim service, support, education and training related to sexual assault and domestic violence.

we are approaching the end of the 60-day notice-and-comment period. we encourage you to join us by reviewing the proposed changes and comment before january 28.

we will continue to fight for all survivors to feel safe and for our community to hold perpetrators accountable.

we believe. we will listen.

call our 24-hour hotline: 716-834-3131.

text:
two years ago, today.

so much has happened since the first women’s march. so. much. from some good, to the bad, to the increasingly unimaginable, the spirit that ignited this movement lives undeterred and with continued cause. to fight for what is fundamentally right and true is to feel like soldiers in a perpetual state of war.

this movement may have foundered since its founding, but what was done, what we chanted, and what empowered us to walk must not be lost on us. truth— the insight to seek it, and the courage to speak it— is the cardinal rule. keep on ✊🏾
(photos: @damonjbarnes)
name: Damon Barnes
tweet_full:
two years ago, today.

so much has happened since the first women’s march. so. much. from some good, to the bad, to the increasingly unimaginable, the spirit that ignited this movement lives undeterred and with continued cause. to fight for what is fundamentally right and true is to feel like soldiers in a perpetual state of war.

this movement may have foundered since its founding, but what was done, what we chanted, and what empowered us to walk must not be lost on us. truth— the insight to seek it, and the courage to speak it— is the cardinal rule. keep on ✊🏾
(photos: @damonjbarnes)

text:
the dream: 
more than 50 years ago dr. king delivered his iconic "i have a dream speech" to around 250,000 people. though we have made great, great strides reaching the dream he spoke about that august day, we haven't quite made it to the vision of freedom he held. 
as we celebrate the day with friends and family, let us not forget those still in shackles, whether physically or mentally. let us raise our voices for those that feel they cannot do it on their own. let us raise our heads, stare injustice down and say, "enough is enough and i won't turn a blind eye." i have a dream. a dream of freedom. freedom from inequality, from abuse, from hate.

won't you join me in spinning this dream into reality?

love and light to the ladies of thrive i adore.
